metrics_conclusion: In terms of chords and melody, Everything Goes On is significantly more complex than the typical song, having above average scores in Chord Complexity, Melodic Complexity, Chord-Melody Tension, Chord Progression Novelty and Chord-Bass Melody.

metadata.editComments: This is probably the weirdest version of the chorus. Mostly because it's accompanied by a guitar using an abnormal tuning. But that guitar was isolated on the stream, so this should be a clear transcription of what it was playing.

I chose to transcribe the second verse because the second half contains a chord change that's similar to the chorus, which does not appear in verse 1. I also have no idea what any of the thirds or chord extensions are doing here because no stems were isolated for this section. I just followed the bassline and the general pattern the song has been following. It's also worth noting that Porter describes the chorus chord progression as a 1 3 6 5 instead of using any inversions.
The following tabs were made by analyzing isolated stems from Porter's live breakdown of this track. Some sections will be uploaded twice because the chord extensions vary with each repetition.

This section is mostly transcribed from the supersaw stem, which has a G and D hanging at the top for most of the chorus. Unfortunately, that only covers the first half. The second half was more transcribed from the full song. The A9 sus4 comes from a B I could just barely hear in the guitar. But I'd say it's subjective.

Mostly based on the live guitar that makes up the bass notes of this section, not including the sampled guitar. If you include the piano, you could add11 to the Em7 chords. But I left it out because it's barely audible and technically starts an 8th note before the chord, so it could almost be considered part of the melody.
I removed the G eighth note from the first syllable of "longer" because I realized it wasn't there.
